:"about 1134","1163":"1163","England":"England","Clotton, Cheshire, England":"Clotton, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rullos","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: altered form of   Tullis  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Tullis","meanings":["Scottish (mainly Fife): probably a habitational name from the lands of Tullois (Fife). The placename appears to be from a Scots plural form of a word borrowed from Gaelic <i>tulach</i> ‘hillock’; compare   Tulloch  ,   Tullie  ."]},{"name":"Tulloss","meanings":["Variant of   Tullos  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":6,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Rullos was born in 1100, in England. He married Mrs Richard Rullos before 1134, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1163, at the age of 63."},"et":{"Abt 1100–Abt 1163":"1100–1163","–Female":"Surnud","1134–Male":"1134–Surnud","1100–1163":"1100–1163","Abt 1163":"1163","1106":"1106","before 1134":"enne 1134","Abt 1100":"1100","1134":"1134","1100":"1100","about 1134":"umbes 1134","1163":"1163","England":"England","Clotton, Cheshire, England":"Clotton, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1100–Abt 1163":"1100–1163","–Female":"Kuollut","1134–Male":"1134–Kuollut","1100–1163":"1100–1163","Abt 1163":"1163","1106":"1106","before 1134":"ennen vuotta 1134","Abt 1100":"1100","1134":"1134","1100":"1100","about 1134":"noin 1134","1163":"1163","England":"England","Clotton, Cheshire, England":"Clotton, Cheshire, England"},"fr":{"Abt 1100–Abt 1163":"1100–1163","–Female":"Décédée","1134–Male":"1134–Décédé","1100–1163":"1100–1163","Abt 1163":"1163","1106":"1106","before 1134":"avant 1134","Abt 1100":"1100","1134":"1134","1100":"1100","about 1134":"environ 1134","1163":"1163","England":"Angleterre","Clotton, Cheshire, England":"Clotton, Cheshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Richard Rullos est né en 1100, à Angleterre. Il a épousé Mrs Richard Rullos avant 1134, à Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé en 1163, à l’âge de 63 ans."},"de":{"Abt 1100–Abt 1163":"1100–1163","–Female":"Verstorben","1134–Male":"1134–Verstorben","1100–1163":"1100–1163","Abt 1163":"1163","1106":"1